The scary thing, hosting internal peer talks, right?

513
00:28:04,485 --> 00:28:07,326
But what we found is that one of the things

514
00:28:07,326 --> 00:28:10,628
that can be really helpful in leadership development

515
00:28:10,628 --> 00:28:12,448
is building someone's presence, right?

516
00:28:12,448 --> 00:28:16,590
The ability to communicate ideas in a compelling way.

517
00:28:16,590 --> 00:28:19,251
And so when we're thinking about that for someone,

518
00:28:19,251 --> 00:28:23,433
we might ask them to prepare and deliver

519
00:28:23,433 --> 00:28:26,835
an internal peer talk on some area of their expertise.

520
00:28:28,635 --> 00:28:31,776
Fixing inherited problems, another awesome way

521
00:28:31,776 --> 00:28:34,957
to build learning into the work itself

522
00:28:34,957 --> 00:28:37,899
and to fill our 70% bucket, particularly when someone

523
00:28:37,899 --> 00:28:41,380
has to go outside of their group to solve a problem, right?

524
00:28:41,380 --> 00:28:44,001
So they might have to go across a discipline

525
00:28:44,001 --> 00:28:46,262
or across another team in the company.

526
00:28:46,262 --> 00:28:49,263
That can be a really effective way.

527
00:28:49,263 --> 00:28:50,004
And scope and scale.

528
00:28:51,157 --> 00:28:51,877
Right?

529
00:28:51,877 --> 00:28:55,280
So maybe I was responsible for this part of the game,

530
00:28:55,280 --> 00:28:57,822
and now I'm responsible for this part of the game.

531
00:28:57,822 --> 00:29:00,264
Or I'm overseeing these functions,

532
00:29:00,264 --> 00:29:03,347
and now you just gave me these functions.

533
00:29:03,347 --> 00:29:07,531
So those kinds of things can also

534
00:29:07,531 --> 00:29:09,272
help how we fill that 70% bucket. 20%.

535
00:29:09,272 --> 00:29:10,393
I can't emphasize it enough.

536
00:29:10,393 --> 00:29:13,235
This 20% bucket is all about support.

537
00:29:13,235 --> 00:29:13,636
Why?

538
00:29:13,636 --> 00:29:19,781
Because learning something new.

539
00:29:20,140 --> 00:29:23,162
is inherently about failing, right?

540
00:29:23,162 --> 00:29:25,222
And failing doesn't feel good.

541
00:29:25,222 --> 00:29:28,604
And so providing a mechanism for people

542
00:29:28,604 --> 00:29:32,445
to talk about those failures and to kick some things around

543
00:29:32,445 --> 00:29:35,967
is really paramount in the learning process.

544
00:29:35,967 --> 00:29:38,348
So examples for us that we use.

545
00:29:38,348 --> 00:29:42,269
So one-on-ones, if there were a soapbox, I would get on it.

546
00:29:42,903 --> 00:29:44,363
I would tell you all to do one-on-ones

547
00:29:44,363 --> 00:29:46,144
if you don't already do them.

548
00:29:46,144 --> 00:29:47,905
But I'm also being very purposeful

549
00:29:47,905 --> 00:29:52,106
about meaningful and effective, those terms used.

550
00:29:52,106 --> 00:29:53,867
Particularly in this case, if we're

551
00:29:53,867 --> 00:29:56,468
thinking about helping to build somebody's leadership

552
00:29:56,468 --> 00:29:57,408
capabilities.

553
00:29:57,408 --> 00:30:00,569
Ideally, those one-on-ones you're having

554
00:30:00,569 --> 00:30:03,810
are less about just the day-to-day tactics

555
00:30:03,810 --> 00:30:06,631
of getting the work done and more about whatever

556
00:30:06,631 --> 00:30:08,812
that thing is that this person's trying to learn.

