00:34:49,700 --> 00:34:50,080
We're busy.

649
00:34:50,080 --> 00:34:58,402
And so the ability though of that art leadership team

650
00:34:58,402 --> 00:35:03,384
to share, to be vulnerable, you know, to talk about things

651
00:35:03,384 --> 00:35:07,685
that are not going well, that actually takes us

652
00:35:07,685 --> 00:35:11,386
to our next rule of prioritizing connection.

653
00:35:11,386 --> 00:35:16,908
And we lean a lot on this rule when we think about building

654
00:35:16,908 --> 00:35:18,928
and strengthening healthy teams.

655
00:35:20,638 --> 00:35:24,419
So we are social creatures.

656
00:35:24,419 --> 00:35:27,159
We are wired to connect to others.

657
00:35:27,159 --> 00:35:30,320
And this rule is how we intentionally

658
00:35:30,320 --> 00:35:34,081
create opportunities for that connection.

659
00:35:34,081 --> 00:35:37,302
And this matters a lot, because connection, at least how

660
00:35:37,302 --> 00:35:40,242
we think about it, is how we build trust,

661
00:35:40,242 --> 00:35:44,003
and in particular, try and get that alignment needed

662
00:35:44,003 --> 00:35:46,504
to manage those conflicts when they do come up,

663
00:35:46,504 --> 00:35:49,285
because they always come up.

664
00:35:50,326 --> 00:35:53,936
And so what inspires some of our thinking behind this

665
00:35:53,936 --> 00:35:55,360
is worth talking about.

666
00:35:55,360 --> 00:35:57,687
And it's based on.

667
00:35:58,642 --> 00:36:01,684
the work of Patrick Lencioni and the book

668
00:36:01,684 --> 00:36:03,985
of Five Dysfunctions of a Team.

669
00:36:03,985 --> 00:36:05,306
Another great read.

670
00:36:05,306 --> 00:36:07,147
Recommend it.

671
00:36:07,147 --> 00:36:10,149
And so really quick, an overview of what

672
00:36:10,149 --> 00:36:14,092
Patrick's book is all about is the first dysfunction

673
00:36:14,092 --> 00:36:16,934
on any team is the absence of trust, right?

674
00:36:16,934 --> 00:36:22,398
So team members do not generally open or honest

675
00:36:22,398 --> 00:36:23,839
with each other.

676
00:36:23,839 --> 00:36:27,221
Impossible to build a healthy foundation of trust,

677
00:36:27,221 --> 00:36:28,262
which leads to.

678
00:36:29,708 --> 00:36:32,212
The second dysfunction, the fear of conflict.

679
00:36:32,212 --> 00:36:33,574
So now I'm not, I don't trust you.

680
00:36:33,574 --> 00:36:36,558
I don't feel comfortable talking about it.

681
00:36:36,558 --> 00:36:38,981
So we don't really have any conflict, right?

682
00:36:38,981 --> 00:36:41,204
It might be like veiled discussions

683
00:36:41,204 --> 00:36:43,347
or very guarded comments.

684
00:36:43,347 --> 00:36:45,230
And so because we're not engaging

685
00:36:45,230 --> 00:36:47,413
in that kind of healthy debate,

686
00:36:47,773 --> 00:36:52,318
a lack of commitment emerges, right, because there's no buy-in.

687
00:36:52,318 --> 00:36:55,723
We haven't been able to have that conversation in a healthy way.

688
00:36:55,723 --> 00:36:58,626
And when there's no buy-in across the teams,

689
00:36:58,626 --> 00:37:00,869
you start to turn to the fourth dysfunction,

690
00:37:00,869 --> 00:37:03,552
which is an avoidance of accountability, right?

691
00:37:03,552 --> 00:37:05,694
It was okay when it left my desk.

692
00:37:05,694 --> 00:37:08,257
Poof, throw it over the wall, like that kind of thing.

693
00:37:08,778 --> 00:37:11,900
And then all of that leads to the fifth dysfunction,

694
00:37:11,900 --> 00:37:12,521
the inattention to results.

695
00:37:12,521 --> 00:37:16,744
And that's where you see really, really unhealthy stuff,

696
00:37:16,744 --> 00:37:21,648
in particular people acting in their own interest,

697
00:37:21,648 --> 00:37:24,210
to feed their own needs of whatever it is, ego

698
00:37:24,210 --> 00:37:30,015
or recognition, instead of putting the needs

699
00:37:30,015 --> 00:37:32,097
of the collective ahead.

700
00:37:32,097 --> 00:37:34,318
So not fun, not a good place to be.

701
00:37:34,318 --> 00:37:37,000
And so our rule of prioritizing connection.

702
00:37:38,161 --> 00:37:42,165
starts at the bottom of this, because that's the foundation.

703
00:37:42,165 --> 00:37:43,726
And so let's talk about that some more.

704
00:37:43,726 --> 00:37:47,510
Because the absence of trust, I'm sure many of you

705
00:37:47,510 --> 00:37:49,572
are like, yeah, Julie, that's super obvious.

706
00:37:50,017 --> 00:37:50,437
Right?

707
00:37:50,437 --> 00:37:52,877
Nothing, no surprising there.

708
00:37:52,877 --> 00:37:56,098
But what Patrick Leccioni was not talking about

709
00:37:56,098 --> 00:37:58,719
was what he called predictive-based trust.

710
00:37:58,719 --> 00:38:01,900
That's the kind of trust that happens

711
00:38:01,900 --> 00:38:05,601
when we've been working together a really long time,

712
00:38:05,601 --> 00:38:07,841
and I know exactly what you're going to say,

713
00:38:07,841 --> 00:38:10,582
and I know exactly what you're going to do

714
00:38:10,582 --> 00:38:13,803
at any given situation.

715
00:38:13,803 --> 00:38:15,363
Right?

716
00:38:15,363 --> 00:38:16,444
Charlie Brown and Lucy.

717
00:38:18,350 --> 00:38:20,410
That kind of trust happens everywhere.

718
00:38:20,410 --> 00:38:21,891
Very easy to get.

719
00:38:21,891 --> 00:38:23,711
What Patrick Lencioni was talking about

720
00:38:23,711 --> 00:38:26,792
was vulnerability-based trust.

721
00:38:26,792 --> 00:38:30,714
And that's the kind of trust that exists.

722
00:38:30,714 --> 00:38:36,075
And you can hear people on teams say things like,

723
00:38:36,075 --> 00:38:37,055
I don't know the answer to that.

724
00:38:37,055 --> 00:38:37,796
I need help.

725
00:38:37,796 --> 00:38:40,056
Or, hey, I'm really sorry.

726
00:38:40,056 --> 00:38:44,118
I was out of line with what I said the other day.

727
00:38:44,118 --> 00:38:45,398
And that's the focus.

728
00:38:48,059 --> 00:38:50,320
of the emphasis on vulnerability-based trust,

729
00:38:50,320 --> 00:38:52,921
and that's what helps.

730
00:38:52,921 --> 00:38:57,283
I guess without it, what happens is things get very politicky,

731
00:38:57,283 --> 00:39:01,946
right, and can turn into these horrible manipulations to win,

732
00:39:01,946 --> 00:39:06,087
right, instead of the assumption of positive intent

733
00:39:06,087 --> 00:39:09,689
and the pursuit of truth, the pursuit of what's

734
00:39:09,689 --> 00:39:10,149
best for the game.

735
00:39:10,149 --> 00:39:12,090
So to build.

736
00:39:12,916 --> 00:39:15,718
healthy amounts of vulnerability-based trust.

737
00:39:15,718 --> 00:39:19,760
Lencioni, in his book, says and suggests

738
00:39:19,760 --> 00:39:23,523
the use of personal histories exercises.

739
00:39:23,523 --> 00:39:23,583
OK.

740
00:39:23,583 --> 00:39:24,644
So if you went back to your teams and you're like, hey,

741
00:39:24,644 --> 00:39:26,025
I saw this cool talk.

742
00:39:26,025 --> 00:39:34,450
And we're going to do some personal histories exercises.

743
00:39:34,450 --> 00:39:40,354
I'm sure you'll get some eyes rolling.

744
00:39:40,354 --> 00:39:40,894
But.

745
00:39:42,373 --> 00:39:46,937
What if you came back and you said, hey, let's try Pikachu?

746
00:39:46,937 --> 00:39:48,939
Everybody likes Pikachu.

747
00:39:48,939 --> 00:39:50,520
It'll be good, right?

748
00:39:50,520 --> 00:39:58,146
This is what we jokingly call, the technical term

749
00:39:58,146 --> 00:39:59,327
is petchakuchas.

750
00:39:59,327 --> 00:40:04,030
And petchakucha means chit-chat in Japanese.

751
00:40:04,030 --> 00:40:07,333
And it's a presentation style that was developed in Japan.

752
00:40:07,863 --> 00:40:11,545
in which 20 slides are shown for 20 seconds each,

753
00:40:11,545 --> 00:40:14,686
so you have a six minute, 40 second presentation.

754
00:40:14,686 --> 00:40:20,829
And it was meant to have really, really concise presentations

755
00:40:20,829 --> 00:40:22,370
that were really fast paced.

756
00:40:22,370 --> 00:40:24,151
And often, they were images only.

757
00:40:24,151 --> 00:40:25,011
There was no text on it.

758
00:40:25,011 --> 00:40:30,594
And I have to thank, actually, GDC four or five years ago

759
00:40:30,594 --> 00:40:35,396
for this idea, because this is not Blizzard's idea.

760
00:40:36,185 --> 00:40:39,666
throw up the pitchy-pitchy thing there.

761
00:40:39,666 --> 00:40:43,968
I sat, a bunch of us went to a talk by a guy named Scott Crabtree.

762
00:40:43,968 --> 00:40:48,429
If you've been to GDC for a long time, he used to do a lot of talks, and it was called

763
00:40:48,429 --> 00:40:48,530
um...

764
00:40:50,538 --> 00:40:55,059
This is your brain on game development.

765
00:40:55,059 --> 00:40:56,980
You can check it out in the vault. It's really cool.

766
00:40:56,980 --> 00:41:00,261
Anyway, but in that talk, he was working at Intel at the time,

